---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import fs from "node:fs";
import path from "node:path";

const svgContent = fs.readFileSync(
  path.join(process.cwd(), "public/diagrams/process-flowchart.svg"),
  "utf-8",
);
---

<Base
  title="The Legal Process"
  description="A visual, step-by-step guide to the entire lifecycle of a § 1983 case in federal court."
>
  <div class="prose">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">The Legal Process</h1>

    <p>
      A § 1983 case in federal court follows a predictable path. Defendants know
      it. Their lawyers know it. Now you will too. Below is every stage of the
      process, who moves, and what's at stake. Click any step in the flowchart
      to jump to that section.
    </p>

    <div
      class="my-10 overflow-x-auto"
      role="img"
      aria-label="Flowchart showing the stages of a § 1983 federal lawsuit from filing through appeal, including interlocutory appeal branches"
    >
      <Fragment set:html={svgContent} />
    </div>

    <p class="text-sm text-slate italic">
      Dashed lines show interlocutory appeals — mid-case appeals that defendants
      use to delay your case.
      <a href="/process/interlocutory-appeal/"
        >Learn how they're abused and what you can do</a
      >.
    </p>

    <hr class="my-10" />

    <h2>Stages</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <a href="/process/preparing-your-case/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow border-l-4 border-green-500"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            1. Preparing Your Case
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            Before you file anything, you need evidence. FOIA requests for body
            camera footage, arrest data, department policies, and statistical
            comparisons — get it all before the complaint, because agencies get
            less cooperative after you sue.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>You move.</strong> Government agencies respond to records requests.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-3 flex gap-3 text-xs">
            <a
              href="/process/foia-and-records-requests/"
              class="text-navy underline decoration-gold hover:text-gold"
              >→ FOIA & Records Requests</a
            >
            <a
              href="/process/organizing-your-war-room/"
              class="text-navy underline decoration-gold hover:text-gold"
              >→ Organizing Your War Room</a
            >
          </div>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/filing/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            2. Filing
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            You file the complaint, pay the fee (or apply for IFP), and get
            summons issued. This is where your case begins — and where IFP
            screening can end it before defendants even know you sued.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>You move.</strong> No opponent yet.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/service/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            3. Service of Process
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            Formally deliver the lawsuit to each defendant. Miss the 90-day
            deadline or serve the wrong person and your case can be dismissed.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>You move.</strong> Defendants receive.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/rule-12-motions/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            4. Rule 12 Motions
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            Defendants attack your complaint before answering it. They'll argue
            you failed to state a plausible claim, the court lacks jurisdiction,
            or qualified immunity bars your suit. This is your first fight.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>Defendant moves.</strong> You respond.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/answer/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            5. Answer & Affirmative Defenses
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            If your complaint survives Rule 12, defendants must respond to each
            allegation — admit, deny, or claim insufficient knowledge. Watch for
            affirmative defenses like qualified immunity and statute of
            limitations.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>Defendant moves.</strong> You read carefully.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/discovery/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            6. Discovery
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            Both sides exchange evidence — documents, written questions,
            depositions. This is where you get the body camera footage, training
            records, and internal files. It's also where most pro se litigants
            get overwhelmed.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>Both sides move.</strong> Discovery is mutual.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/summary-judgment/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            7. Summary Judgment
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            Defendants ask the court to end your case without a trial. They'll
            argue there's no genuine factual dispute — and qualified immunity
            comes back for round two. This is the second gate.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>Usually defendant moves.</strong> You respond with evidence.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/interlocutory-appeal/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow border-l-4 border-red-400"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            ⚠ Interlocutory Appeal
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            When a court denies qualified immunity, defendants can appeal
            immediately — freezing your case for 6-18 months. They can do this
            twice: once at Rule 12, once at summary judgment. It's the single
            most effective delay weapon in § 1983 litigation.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>Defendant moves.</strong> You defend in the circuit court.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/pretrial/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            8. Pretrial
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            The court prepares for trial — conferences, motions in limine,
            exhibit and witness lists, jury instructions. Settlement pressure
            intensifies here. This is where cases end or get real.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>Both sides move.</strong> Court manages.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/trial/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            9. Trial
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            You present your evidence to a judge or jury. You go first (burden
            of proof). Jury selection, opening statements, witness examination,
            closing arguments, verdict. Nothing like TV.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>You present first.</strong> Defendant follows.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>

      <a href="/process/post-trial-and-appeal/" class="block group">
        <article
          class="p-5 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:shadow-md transition-shadow"
        >
          <h3
            class="text-lg font-semibold text-navy group-hover:text-gold transition-colors"
          >
            10–11. Post-Trial & Appeal
          </h3>
          <p class="text-slate text-sm mt-1">
            After the verdict: motions for new trial, relief from judgment, fee
            petitions. If you lose (or win and they appeal), the case goes to
            the circuit court. You have 30 days to file notice of appeal — miss
            it and it's over. This deadline cannot be waived.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate mt-2">
            <strong>Either side can move.</strong> 30-day appeal deadline is jurisdictional.
          </p>
        </article>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
